{
  "doc_id": "10757",
  "text": "The PASS-20 is a self-report rating scale that measures pain-related trait anxiety. [CITATION_1] The questionnaire consists of six sub-scales measuring cognitive, fear, escape/avoidance, and physiological aspects of pain-related anxiety. PASS-20 consists of 20 items comprising statements such as \"I can't think straight when in pain\". Participants were required to indicate how often they identify with the statement on a 6-point Likert scale (0= \"never\", 5= \"always\"). The sum of each item in the PASS-20 ranges from 0 to 100, in which a higher score indicates higher pain-related trait anxiety. The PASS-20 has exhibited an excellent internal consistency in previous studies (α=0.91) and correlates highly with its original form (r=0.95). [CITATION_2] The questionnaire has generally exhibited a high correlation with other widely used self-report pain-related anxiety measures such as the Fear of Pain Questionnaire-III, suggesting a strong convergent validity (r=0.53). [CITATION_3] The excellent internal consistency is also replicated in this sample with a Cronbach's α of 0.89.",
